===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*sek-}}
{{root|en|ine-pro|*sekʷ-|id=follow}}
From {{inh|en|enm|secte}}, from {{der|en|fro|secte||a sect in philosophy or religion}}, from {{der|en|LL.|secta||a sect in philosophy or religion, a school, party, faction, class, gild, band, particularly a heretical doctrine or sect, etc.}}, possibly, from {{der|en|la|sequi||to follow}}. Alternatively linked to {{m|la|sectus||cut off, divided}}, past participle of {{m|la|secō}}.<!--Century 1911 has the derivation from "secare" as the main one through "secare viam" (take one's way, travel), discussing three alternative explanations as less probable: two of them from "sequi", one more from "secare". M-W online traces the origin to "sequi", so does Online Etymology Dictionary.-->

